We can understand the Terraform state file like the memory of our infrastructure. When this file is deleted, Terraform forgets everything it created.
ğŸ‘‰ ğ–ğ¡ğšğ­ ğğ±ğšğœğ­ğ¥ğ² ğ¡ğšğ©ğ©ğğ§ğ¬?
Terraform loses the complete mapping of resources.
Terraform thinks all resources are new.
Terraform may try to recreate existing infrastructure, leading to conflicts, errors, or downtime.

ğŸ‘‰ ğ–ğ¡ğ² ğ¢ğ¬ ğ­ğ¡ğ¢ğ¬ ğğšğ§ğ ğğ«ğ¨ğ®ğ¬?
We cannot safely run plan or apply.
We cannot update or destroy resources correctly.
We may accidentally break production by creating duplicate resources.

ğŸ‘‰ ğ‡ğ¨ğ° ğœğšğ§ ğ°ğ ğšğ¯ğ¨ğ¢ğ ğ­ğ¡ğ¢ğ¬?
Always store state in remote backend like S3 + DynamoDB, Azure Storage + Locks, GCS, etc.
Enable state locking.
Take regular backups of the state file.

ğŸ’¡ ğ’ğ¡ğ¨ğ«ğ­ ğšğ§ğ¬ğ°ğğ«: If the state file is deleted, Terraform loses track of your infrastructure and may try to recreate everything.

