We can use variables in Terraform to make our code simple, reusable, and easy to manage. Terraform mainly supports three types of variables:

ğŸ”¹ ğˆğ§ğ©ğ®ğ­ ğ•ğšğ«ğ¢ğšğ›ğ¥ğğ¬
 We use input variables to pass values from outside when we run terraform plan or terraform apply. These values can come from .tfvars files, CLI arguments, or environment variables.

ğŸ”¹ ğ‹ğ¨ğœğšğ¥ ğ•ğšğ«ğ¢ğšğ›ğ¥ğğ¬
 We use local variables for internal calculations or static values. They work only inside the module or folder where the Terraform command runs. They help us avoid repeating values and keep the code clean.

ğŸ”¹ ğğ®ğ­ğ©ğ®ğ­ ğ•ğšğ«ğ¢ğšğ›ğ¥ğğ¬
 We use output variables to show important values after Terraform finishes. Other modules and pipelines can read these outputs. This helps us share required information from the state.

ğŸ’¡ We can use these three variable types to build clean, scalable, and production-ready Terraform modules.
